This grocery store with its eatery / tavern serving 'mas sabor' Mexican fare and cold cervezas to a well stocked contemporary Latin jukebox in the rear has understandably popular appeal to a diverse local, Mexican and Latin community. A local authentic gem  within a predominant orthodox hasidic neighborhood, the great local feel vibe and experience can get upstaged by the understaffed service on popular evenings that all tables are taken, the takeout calls are nonstop, and the grocery store becomes unmanned. Their 'sopa de pollo' is pure comfort on some chilly evening, and the reach in cold display upfront has all you will ever need in an emergency to put together a fresh mean quick salsa, pico de gallo and/or guacamole.

i want to preface this with- some of the things i mention in my review could potentially be attributed to the time of night i ordered my food- 1230am- they close at 1am- but they were close enough where i didn't think it'd be a major inconvenience. I ordered chips and guac for 7.99, guac was worth it but there weren't that many chips and some oil was still floating around at the bottom of the container. i also ordered torta, requested some things be substituted with things i know they have (as listed on other parts of the menu) but didn't get any of it. they were quite soggy and plain. All together i spent 18 dollars to have it delivered because i was crazy hungry. trust, i am full of buyers remorse and less than mediocre food. also, i specially requested they not buzz my building but instead call me, left my number, which they ignored. note to self- next time, get off your ass, buy some goldfish and call it a night.

There are two parts: the small grocery in front and the smallish restaurant in back.  I got a veggie burrito and it was pretty good. It had that authentic shredded cheese and surprisingly good sour cream on top.  Unfortunately while I was eating the restaurant literally flooded. They mopped up the floor around me as I ate.  Although it's basically a counter service joint the lady made the effort to come and serve me. But she gave me the wrong change, cutting me short a bit.  I do not plan to return.

One of those hidden, back-of-the-bodega taquerias, this one is actually pretty spacious and has plenty of tables and chairs if you'd like to dine in, though most opt for take-out/delivery. I've only gotten the burritos here, which come in a box covered with awesome sauce and cheese, and some salad on the side for greenery. A great neighborhood option for a casual lunch.
Hidden gem on Myrtle Ave. in the back of a deli serving great Mexican food. You can grab beers from the drink fridge and there's usually soccer on the TV. Try the goat tacos, they're amazing.
